title: C# Basics
categories: C# Programming
---
Variables are an important aspect of programming. They can be defined by doing this:

```csharp
e.g.
double poundToDollarRate = 1.67;
const double dollarToPoundRate = 0.59;
double finalValue;
```

As seen above, constants can be made by further defining the variables as constants.


With variables, values can be converted, from one data type to another, for example:

```csharp
e.g.
string origInput = Console.ReadLine();
double origValue = Convert.ToDouble(origInput);
```

Above, a string input variable has been converted to a decimal data type.


Switch - Case is a more advanced form of if statements, they can be written like this:

```csharp
e.g.
switch(iX)
{
  case 1:
    finalValue = origValue * dollarToPoundRate;
    Console.WriteLine(origValue + " dollars are worth " + finalValue + " pounds.");
    Console.ReadLine();
    break;
  case 2:
    finalValue = origValue * poundToDollarRate;
    Console.WriteLine(origValue + " pounds are worth " + finalValue + " dollars.");
    Console.ReadLine();
    break;
  default:
    Console.WriteLine("Incorrect Value inputted.");
    Console.ReadLine();
    break;
}
```
